## вљ пёЏ Security Improvements Over PHP Version

> [!CAUTION]
> The PHP codebase has **critical security vulnerabilities** that must be fixed in migration.

| Issue | PHP Version | Next.js Fix |
|---|---|---|
| **SQL Injection** | Direct string interpolation in queries: `"WHERE username='$email_login'"` | Prisma ORM with parameterized queries |
| **Plaintext Passwords** | Stored as-is in `usertbl` | bcrypt hashing with `cost=12` |
| **No CSRF protection** | Plain HTML forms with `POST` | Next.js built-in CSRF + NextAuth tokens |
| **Session fixation** | `session_destroy()` + `session_start()` pattern is fragile | NextAuth JWT sessions |
| **No input validation** | Raw `$_POST` values used directly | Zod schema validation on all API routes |

---

## рџ“Љ Verification Plan

### After Phase 1
- Login with all 4 role types and verify correct redirects
- Confirm middleware blocks unauthorized role access

### After Phase 2 (Data Migration)
- SQL count check: `SELECT class, COUNT(*) FROM students GROUP BY class` must match original
- Verify 10 random students can log in with their mobile number as password

### After Phase 3
- Add a new student в†’ appears in list в†’ edit в†’ verify changes persisted
- Create exam в†’ add subjects в†’ input marks в†’ view result

### After Phase 4
- Record a fee payment в†’ check receipt generated в†’ monthly status updates to "Paid"

### After Phase 5
- Student login в†’ view own result page and fee status (cannot see other students)
- Teacher login в†’ can input marks only for assigned subjects

### Final
- Side-by-side comparison of result reports between old PHP and new Next.js for same student
